observations.recommendation:
We recommended and Management agreed to –
a. instruct the Inventory Committee to-
(i) conduct annual physical count of PPE and upon completion of the physical count, reconcile the result of actual count with the existing inventory records; (ii) prepare the RPCPPE in prescribed format and submit the same to the Office of the Auditor on or before January 31 of the following year; and (iii) ensure that all PPEs are properly tagged with property stickers for easy identification; 
b. direct the Municipal Accountant to –
➢ effect the necessary adjustments for the PPE accounts for (i) reclassification of PPE accounts that were erroneously charged to incorrect PPE account title; and (ii) amortization expense based on the installation date of the PATAS; ➢ record small tangible items with estimated useful life of more than one year and with amount valued below ₱15,000.00 as inventories upon acquisition and as expense upon issuance; ➢ include disclosures relating to unserviceable and/or held for disposal assets in the Notes to Financial Statements under ‘Property, Plant, and Equipment’ based on the list submitted by the Inventory Committee; and ➢ effect the eventual derecognition/dropping from the books of the disposed properties based on required supporting documents for proper presentation of the accounts in the financial statements; 
c. require the GSO to prepare, maintain, and update Property Cards for each PPE item; 
d. instruct the Appraisal and Disposal Committee to facilitate disposal of unserviceable assets pursuant to Section 79 of PD 1445; and 
e. consider the implementation of the one-time cleansing of PPE accounts per COA Circular No. 2020-006.

We recommended and Management agreed to –
a. communicate with the Office of the Provincial Assessor and/or Office of the Provincial Treasurer, thru official letter, regarding the problems found or concerns on the system of the Treasurer’s Office in order to attain full utilization of the system as intended thus, maximizing the cost incurred therefor and attaining the objectives of facilitating the efficient processing of real property transactions and increasing tax collections;
b. instruct the Municipal Treasurer to
(i) implement procedures and strategies on how to further improve collection efficiency; such as raffle of prizes to early bird taxpayers.
(ii) publish yearly the notice of delinquency once a week for two consecutive weeks in a newspaper of general circulation;
(iii) include remarks/statement regarding the reason/s for non-collection or non-payment in the certified list of all real property tax delinquencies which remained uncollected or unpaid for at least one year, with a request for assistance in the enforcement of the remedies for collection submitted to the Sanggunian; and
(iv) prepare duly certified list showing the name of taxpayers and the amount due and collectible for the year and copy furnish the Municipal Accountant;
c. require the Municipal Accountant to (i) maintain the corresponding subsidiary ledgers (SLs) in support of the RPT and SET Receivable balances so that reconciliation be made with the MTO; and (ii) make necessary adjustment to reflect the correct amount of RPT/SET Receivable and its respective Deferred Credits based on the results of reconciliation made; and
d. direct the Municipal Assessor to expedite the updating of Assessment Roll which is the basis for the collection of RPT and for the updating of Real Property Tax Account Register (RPTAR) by the MTO which will then be submitted to the Municipal Accounting Office for the set-up of receivables at the beginning of the year.

