We recommended and the Municipal Mayor agreed to instruct the –
BAC, BAC Secretariat and BAC TWG to –
justify in writing, the reason for awarding the contract to the winning bidder despite the deficiencies in the bidding documents submitted; and
make themselves knowledgeable of the procurement law by attending seminars facilitated by duly accredited trainors and observe strict compliance with the revised IRR of RA No. 9184 regarding conduct of competitive bidding and evaluate thoroughly the completeness and correctness of bid documents submitted by the bidders to ensure that legally, technically and financially capable contractor/supplier is awarded with the contract;
BAC Secretariat to –
adher with the posting requirements set under revised IRR of RA No. 9184 to promote effective competition and transparency in the procurement process; and
ensure that the Contract Agreement is supported with an SB Resolution authorizing the Municipal Mayor to enter into a contract;
Municipal Engineer to –
ensure that the Program of Works is duly supported with the required schedules to support the materials, quantity and time duration indicated therein;
ensure compliance with the requirements of relevant DILG MC in the implementation and monitoring of projects funded under LGSF-AM;
prepare quality control plan for each infrastructure projects in accordance with the DPWH Standard Specifications for Highways, Bridges, and Airports, 1998, Volume II and require the contractor to submit the minimum test results issued by duly accredited testing laboratories for specific item of works as identified in the quality control plan;
cause the contractor to submit original and completed copy of duly approved CSHP in accordance with DOLE DO No. 13 series of 1998 prior to start of the project;
ensure that infrastructure projects are covered with Contractor’s All Risk Insurance; and
conduct final inspection of the project, one year after its completion and cause the issuance of Certificate of Final Acceptance and posting of warranty security for structural defects and failures effective for one year from the date of issuance of Certificate of Final Acceptance.

We recommended and the Management agreed to require the:

(a) Inventory Committee complete the conduct of the annual physical count of PPE and inventory and submit RPCPPE and RCPI, respectively, to the Office of the Auditor not later than the prescribed deadline stated in the Manual;

(b) Accounting Office to update PPE and Real Property Ledger Cards and the GSO cause the preparation and maintenance of complete and updated Property Cards to enable reconciliation with the general ledger balances and the inventory report, and monitor improvement and disposition of each property;

(c) OIC-GSO (i) maintain property cards for each property for monitoring and reconciliation; (ii) continue the identification of unserviceable properties to cause its appraisal and inspection for disposal; and (iii) follow necessary procedures on proper disposal of these properties.

We commended the Management in providing necessary support in enjoining the barangays to establish their MRF and to promote compliance with segregation. 

We also recommended and the Management agreed to:

a.) take appropriate action to ensure that the existing MRF of the component barangays be fully functional; 

b.) strictly comply with the specific requirements of the Act in the segregation, collection and transport of solid wastes to the MRF; 

d.) assign capable personnel to validate the services provided for the residual waste disposal and garbage collection services to support the claim and prepare the inspection and acceptance report;

f.) continue their efforts and initiative to include operating a Sanitary Landfill in the long-term plan.

