We reiterated our recommendation and the Management agreed that the Municipal Accountant 

(a) strictly monitor and conduct regular and periodic verification, analysis, and validation of the existence of the receivables; 

(b) prepare necessary adjusting entries for transactions affecting receivables; 

(c) prepare aging of dormant receivables, unliquidated cash advances and fund transfers on a quarterly basis to support the request for write-off, and indicate in the remarks column the existence of the applicable conditions; and 

(d) request for write-off of uncollectible receivables from the books of accounts to the Commission on Audit supported by documents required by the Circular.

We recommended and the Management agreed that the:

(a) Inventory Committee continue to complete the conduct of the annual physical inventory of PPE by description type and submit a report thereon to the Office of the Auditor not later than January 31 of each year; 

(b) OIC-GSO cause the preparation and maintenance of complete and updated Property Cards to enable reconciliation with the general ledger balances and the inventory report, and monitor improvement and disposition of each property;

(c) Municipal Accountant verify all the parcels of land owned by the municipality in the listings of Land from the Municipal Assessor and locate possible documentations pertaining thereto to support recording of Land account; and 

(d)    OIC-GSO (i)continue the identification of unserviceable properties to cause its appraisal and inspection for disposal; (ii) follow procedures on proper disposal of these properties; and (iii) maintain property cards for each property for monitoring and reconciliation.

We reiterated our recommendations and the Management agreed to  

(a) retrieve the required documents and coordinate with the previous owners of the motor vehicles for the transfer of the registration; 

(b) prepare necessary documents for the transfer of donated vehicles; 

(c) prepare the Inventory and Inspection Report of Unserviceable Property (IIRUP) to undertake proper disposal of unserviceable motor vehicles; and 

(d) initiate investigation to determine accountable officials and employees responsible for the missing equipment and file appropriate charges, if warranted.

We recommended and the Management agreed that 

(a) through the Solid Waste Management Board, encourage active participation of barangay officials to educate their respective constituents on the proper segregation of reusable or recyclable materials from compostable wastes;

 (b) take appropriate action to ensure that the existing MRF of the component barangays be fully functional; 

(c) assign an a capable personnel to validate the services provided by Metro Clark to support the claim and prepare the inspection and acceptance report; 

(d) ensure that all transactions are supported with complete documentation in accordance with Section 4(6) of PD No. 1445; 

(e) Refund the overpayment made on December 13, 2017 amounting to ₱69,000.00 or an equivalent to 57.50 tons and 

(f) continue their efforts and initiative to include operating a Sanitary Landfill in the long term plan.

